column5: Comments
Very clear in what he says and is very approachable. Kind of funny sometimes. Tries to be engaging although the topics he covers can often be pretty boring, but, for me at least, the content was eas

Kind of funny, but mostly boring. He just reads a UMass Boston professor's lecture notes to the class for an hour and a half and calls it a day. Doesn't seem to care too much about teaching. Not too horrible if you're stuck with him, but there are much better profs for this course.

I thought he went through the material too fast. He assumed that we had all covered a lot of this stuff previously, but before his class I had never done truth tables or sets or logic, so he didn't explain it all clearly enough for me. It wasn't a hard class though. Pretty easy for CMSC majors. I'm a math major tho so it wasn't quite as easy.
The class is very boring. he drops a lot of stuff. easy to get a B in class without much effor but make sure you understand the material, you will need it in 313 and 341.

To elaborate a bit more... He does drop the lowest scores out of hw, tests, and group assignments. Alt. - his attendance scoring seems rather arbitrary throughout the years. Best advice - just study past tests, memorize how to do it his way, and you should be OK! Otherwise, don't think you're right if you answer isn't solved using his approach.
Just to revise my previous post: althoug there are 4hws,3inclasses,and 3 tests, you can drop the lowest of each leaving only 3 hws, 2 inclasses and 2 tests factored into your grade

I sware he looks like peter from Family guy , Clearly explains what you need to know and has all old exams available to students. All you need to do is the old exams and your set , but the theories / theroms are kind of hard but hey there is a curve
I've had much worse. He's funny, entertaining, and helpful, and makes a daunting class a lot more tolerable. I just wish he'd teach Math and Stat.
You have to be an idiot not to pass his class. He hand feeds to everything you need to know. Just pay attention sometimes. Likeable, positive, easy-going man.

This professor is probably the funniest professor of all time! He makes jokes out of nowhere. I really recomend him for all of you taking(or will take) computer science. He makes everything easy to understand.Looks:he looked like the dad in "Family
Not professional. Strays off topic often, not articulate. Lectures are very disorganized, and the slides are ripped off the java textbook. Exams require hard memorization of java definitions.

Average professor at best. Teaching style consists of a class discussion, which is useless since most students don't know the material ahead of time. Strays off topic often, likes to talk about video games during class. Would not recommend.
Makes things more complicated than they actually are. If you have to take this professor, don't get caught up on the tangents he explores. Most of it is irrelevant on the exams.

Overall, I recommend his class because he does help to understand the information. The one issue I had was sometimes I would raise my hand and he would see it but then go help someone else. Also, it's a boring class and most people don't pay attention. So when he asks someone a question he spends 10 minutes making them understand.
Go to class! Exams are exactly what is covered in class. Projects are pretty easy since I had Java in High School.

Death by PowerPoint. Most of the slides are ripped straight from Addison-Wesley's Java slides. Projects can be modified w/o due date extensions. Was not very responsive via email. Did not honor arrangements discussed during office hours. Associates well with the younger crowd, but otherwise borderline average.

Everyone seems to not like him very much or says he's a bad teacher, but I like him. He's a lot easier to talk to than some of the other professors and I learn a lot in his classes. That's why I'm taking 341H with him Fall 2010. How many other professors can you talk about MW2 or the Starcraft 2 beta with before class?

Had her for 104 and 201. She really made it easy to learn basic programming concepts. Tests were basically the study guides and were much easier than the homeworks (which weren't too difficult, but challenging sometimes). I definitely would recommend her if you need to take either course.

The class can be a little boring if you go everyday and understand everything. The labs are very helpful in practicing each concept and I would definitely at least flip through the book from time to time. It proved very helpful. Ms. Block and the TAs were very helpful through email. They won't give you the answer but will send you in the right way

Professor Block is absolutely Beautiful. She should be a news anchor or something. Honestly, attendance is not mandatory but I did go to all classes. Who wouldn't! She's cool AND hot AND knows computers.
A truly horrible teacher

Absolutely the worst, arrogant teacher ever. Does not explain anything, and when emailed, he doesn't reply. We use no text books and basically you're on your own for projects. Please do not make the mistake of taking him. He can make even the simplest thing a problem from hell. PLEASE DO NOT TAKE HIM.

He is really funny. Read before lectures then go to class and you should understand everything. For me I just went to class and sometimes I was lost, but I would ask questions. Material builds upon itself so don't fall behind. Midterm was long so time yourself. Final was doable except the last design problem. Labs are easy. Homeworks take time.

I don't get why some people don't like this guy. He's hilarious. His class is like comedy night. As for the actual material, he expects a lot from his students so be warned, it's not easy. You can afford to miss some classes so that's cool. His exams though, are mostly easy except for the last few design problems, so better get used to design probs
do not recommend.

He's a really smart guy and knows what he's talking about, so I think he just assumes we understand the material 100% when he explains it. His tests are really hard. There was no fill in the blank code on exams, the second part of the exam is just writing code. He puts up sample exams which are really similar to his actual exams, so study those.

His lectures are boring. Tests , projects and even some labs are tough. Its hard to get an A. Good at clearing doubts, and replying emails. Reading textbook will help understanding it better. 202 is rough so be prepared well in advance. DO NOT just depend on instructor

Explains things well, class is interesting and was a major part of what I learned. For Algorithms, he doesn't do midterms, just a handful of quizzes throughout the semester and a final at the end (which was pretty much 4 quizzes stapled together.)
Didn't use textbook. Was helpful somewhat but sometimes you were totally on your own but did have help from ta. Some quizzes were easy others were harder and final exam was ok.

This was my least favorite class of the semester. MAybe Im just not a computer science fan. I cant believe this is an introductory course. We had short quizzes he was lenient with grading but over all I still didnt like the class

Junior in college and this is easily one of the worst professors I have ever had. Might be good at teaching upper level classes but not lower. Gives wayyy to much work and its harder than it should be on top of that trying to figure out my grade is impossible. Its like trying to debug a program in itself it makes no sense. keep it real truth hurts.
terrible at an entry level class. way to much work. very bad at introducing the subject.

Doesn't show much interest in the students. He seems to be just there to collect a paycheck. 15+ minutes late to class every day. Didn't show up at least once without any warning or even a mention of it the next day of class. He doesn't clearly explain what will be on exams which are very hard. Awful at answering student questions.

Teaches directly out of textbook, gives extremely difficult MATLAB projects with holes and typos, exams are difficult as well and he refuses to let you know what is on them, not helpful when asking questions. Can be a nice guy when just talking casually. Painful experience but in the end he graded with a massive curve.
He knows his stuff but can't teach worth a damn. He can't explain anything very well or at all so don't bother asking questions. Pretty much teach yourself from the book. He is useless.

Terrible, terrible, teacher. Makes this class much harder than it has to be. He is not clear in his explanations and reads straight from slides. When he does write on the board its illegible. This class will make you hate computer engineering. Based on my experience in this class, I switched majors. Wait and take it with LeBerge

Very long and boring lectures. Bother your TA for help. Definitely study the homework before tests. Just about all his test problems were straight from the homework. Since he's here for the research he doesn't really care about the grades, seems like most of us got B's even with how bad we did on the tests.

Choa is like most grad. profs who get assigned this course: not very helpful. Very nice guy, though. This is basic circuit theory so it doesn't much matter. Homeworks are extremely hard and time consuming; exams are killer but he puts some HW problems on them. Choa curves so study your ass off and do good on labs & HW and you can swing a B.

Lectures were a little boring as she often read directly off the powerpoint (but you could just read them on your own and not go). Labs are crucial because they prepare you for the homework. Overall I thought it was very easy (though I am a CMSC major), but the final project is considerably more difficult than anything else in the class.

As others have said, you don't need to go to lecture, just read the slides online and show up for labs. Homeworks are pretty easy, the last project is a lot harder than anything else in the course but still not too bad.

Her class is Death by PowerPoint (HTML Slidy). You could easily skip the lecture and just show up for the labs and exams; a lot of people did. Doesn't allow basic CS flow control stuff like "break" and "continue" in assignments. Final project was too abstract with relation to what was taught. Graders "nickel and dime" assignments. Rigid style.

This teacher is terrible if you really want to learn. She confesses that she does not know that material until the week of class. Her lectures consist of her reading word for word off the slides which are online anyways, so going to class is a waste of time, but you can't just rely on the slides because she constantly has errors on them.

This teacher seems to know little to nothing on the subject matter. She reads directly off her powerpoints during lectures, and even states that she is still learning the material with us. The projects are all fairly easy if you know what youre doing, but her requirements in coding style are absurd and unnecessary.

Evans is awesome. She's very helpful when you go to office hours, and class really isn't too hard (though lecture can get boring). All the lecture notes r online. Just make sure you pace yourself n unless you REALLY know what you're doing don't leave the projects until the last day. Go to labs, they help with the projects, and do the review sheets.

I'm a minor with previous 3 years of Java and I didn't think the class was too bad. Tests are easy, projects are in C, but they were ok. You don't need the book and you might want to go to lab to do the projects. First time I fell asleep in a class though. Don't buy the book.

You don't need to attend class, you just need to understand how to read the lecture slides. She doesn't explain the projects very well, but if you shoot her an email, she will get back to you promptly and help you out. Exams are super easy. The easiest way to do well in this course is talk to someone who has taken it before.

Her lectures are pointless, you wont learn anything by going to class. Projects are a little tough but if you know what you're doing, you're fine. She doesn't curve grades even if you are on the border line, she doesn't care for her students no matter how extreme your situation is. Don't take her,especially if its a gateway course,you'll be screwed

Very good professor. Class isn't difficult, but is challenging enough to keep you interested. Textbooks aren't really needed, mainly to look up coding nuances. Lecture notes online and clear. Evans is very open to assisting students, and was very helpful when my program had a bug that was actually the system's fault, not mine.

He's leaving, so maybe this review is irrelevant. Projects are more difficult or more time consuming than they appear. Start on day one. Literally. Exams were kind of difficult, but doable with more studying. Nice guy but not an easy class.
He is a really fair teacher. explain information really clearly. Projects are hard. 341 is a hard course he is already did pretty good. I am really enjoy in his class

Went into that class with 3 years of Java experience. I attended class anyways, but if you already know it you probably don't have to. He's a nice guy and very approachable. Tries to make projects interesting and they aren't too difficult. Go to labs.

Worst Teacher Ever, I don't know why he has such a high rating. He grades super hard, doesn't give partial credit. If something is out of 10 points you can either get a 0, 5, or 10. So that's a 0%, 50%, or 100%. So if you're not perfect, you fail. Avoid if possible.

Went through lecture slides too fast - too many slides to print & no computers allowed. Pop quizzes unreasonably difficult and unrelenting. Overly strict & seemed to care more about making things easier on himself. Participation credit policy was completely screwed up - only one point a day, and only from answering a question in class correctly.

Like the other people said, it is a very challenging class. Don't take many classes if you want to take his class so that you'll have enough time to read the book. Read the book thoroughly before and after the class. Pop quizzes and 3 difficult exams. Be prepared to be challenged if you choose this professor.

I found this class to be very hard. The person below probably knew a lot about computers before taking the course whereas I knew how to turn it on. I'm getting a B. We had a presentation that had NOTHING to do with the class, it would fit IS300 well, NOT 310, it was a waste of time. I learned a lot but for me it was hard to do great on his exams.

Who ever complains about him HAS TO BE STUPID enough not to do well in his class. He Understands that the course is hard and curves the grade. I would recommend anyone to take his class!! I would advise everyone to go to cls everyday, make sure u participate and read the text BOOK. That is guarantied a B. He like students who participate

What a jerk. I was 2 minutes late to class and he wouldn't let me take one of his pop quizzes. His tests are impossibly hard and his class is impossibly boring. Not a lot of work though if you are smart enough to learn the material on your own.

He's not stupid but he really doesn't know much about the IS field and teaches out dated info from old slides. He is a terrible teacher tho and can't explain the material or what he expects on any assignment. Tests are medium to hard depending on how much you read out of class, but he gives no grading feedback at all, and very boring. Avoid.

Bad. Gave us 10 papers + group projects and refused to grade ANY of it until after the final was over. Tests are crazy detailed and cover way too much. Never really knew what was going on until the very end. I got a B and i have no idea why. take it with somebody else

grading sucks, no idea wtf was going on with grades....thought was failing the class cuz his exams were ungodly hard. not a thing related to what was gone over in the class. pretty much teaches from the slides as well...def take other guy; redding over this guy if you can

Being another required class for the IS gateway it is relatively easy if you have even the slightest bit of knowledge about computer hardware and concepts. As long as the powerpoint slides are read the information is not that difficult to understand. The class gets boring sometimes but it is not that difficult.
exams are short answer questions are from a list, easy ish class but ben stein is more interesting than him
Boring, very basic for a 300-level class (if you can't grok this stuff you shouldn't be an IFSM major). Exams not especially difficulty, but you must go to class -- absences can/will drop your grade.

This class is weird. Lots of technical stuff, unapplicable to anything, except for the geeks, they were in heaven. Mr Green is fair. Read the book before class and score 3 xtra credit points, they'll come in handy. Aim to score better than the rest of the class everyexam 2 get an A. It worked for me

Very knowledgeable professor and good adviser. Discusses the math and logic behind all algorithms and methods discussed in class. Lectures may be heavy for most, you really need to be attentive and not zone out.

So here's the thing -- he's an amusing lecturer, and I did learn useful information from this class. That's a win. This is UMBC we are talking about here, I don't think you can ask for much more. The class is insanely tough. But he does EPIC CURVES (60%+ avg seemed to be an A). But you will not have any clue what your grade is until the end.

Easily the worst professor I have had in my entire college career. First exam average was 27%. Learned nothing the entire semester. I ended up with a C with a final score of 31%. Highest grade in class was 65%. I would have avoided, but it was the only section offered this semester which was my last. Plan ahead to take this with someone else.

First, I'm a Math/CMSC major. Kalpakis is extremely difficult, in part because his proofs for are not rigorous at all. The other part is that the hws and exams expect different skills from you, so don't look to the hw to study. The exams have no partial credit; writing an alg gets no points if you don't answer the accompanied questions.

He doesn't care about his course. He acts as if he cares, but the TA shoulders the entire thing. TA decides on the project specifications, deadlines. TA makes the questions for the exams. You ask him something, he says he has to ask the TA. Final exam had the exam same q's as the midterm so remember the midterm! Happily, grades very easy.

An entertaining lecturer and knows the material well. Exams are very hard. Homeworks are from the book, so if you read the book theoretically you should do fine on those. The semester project wasn't terribly involved, but extremely tedious. He said he would make changes for future semesters. Definitely expects students to read the book.

Projects were difficult but very feasable if you allowed the necessary time. The tests however were very hard but come from the book, which he expects you to fully read and remember the assigned chapters. Most hw comes from the book and answers can be found in the previous edition solution manual

His lectures were interesting, and he is very smart. I enjoyed operating systems up until I got my final grade. The TAs didn't grade half of my projects and homework(even though he promised we would see all of our grades before the final) so I got a C in the class. I emailed him several times to see if I could get a regrade. He he responded after a

Class isn't all that hard, but Katz is a poor teacher. Just writes on the chalk board and expects you to follow along. His answers to questions are often vague and sometimes he doesn't really answer you
Horrible handwriting, lectures on blackboard, no Power Point, is deaf, doesn’t follow textbook, and forgets to write down grades. He is drier than a bad yeast infection.

Katz works with you if you work with him. True he does have trouble hearing and his midterm was the worst, but its like 15% of your grade. He mostly looks at projects and homework as well as the final. I printed out all his slides from the lecture. That and the comp sci help desk helped me to pass.

Nice guy, lousy teacher. Mostly deaf so comunication with him is very difficult. All notes were handwritten on chalkboard in chicken scratch. Could not read them. Ask questions of him at your own peril. Having Burt as co-teacher only made things worse.

Worst teacher I have ever had in my life. He gives hard tests for an easy class, The average scores for the tests are low c's or high d's. He is also deaf. The directions for the projects are unclear. I think I know excel better than him.

Again, nice guy, HORRIBLE teacher. Waste of time coming to class, I did the same just reading the slides at home. Does not give back graded projects in time to learn from your mistakes. Avoid - if at all possible.

341 is tough no matter what, but Lupoli made it bearable. May seem harsh sometimes, but that's just his sense of humor. Don't be afraid to go to his office hours if you don't understand something - he's actually really nice and helpful. Projects are time consuming, but not too bad if you pay attention in class and use Piazza.
Very unclear assignments that did not match the material we were being taught.

Good guy. I've had him for 3 classes. You'll have to do work, but nothing too difficult. He makes mistakes and sometimes his TAs mess up but I still recommend taking a class with him. Makes jokes; don't take it personally. What I've gained from his classes has helped me land a solid internship.

Lupoli is a tough teacher that can come off as a bit rude but he actually cares about the material and structures his classes so that you LEARN. I have landed a great internship based solely off of the database material he taught in CMSC 331 and have done well on interviews because of the material he covered in CMSC 341. I would take his class.

331 with Lupoli is very, very hard. The in-class labs are hard to complete, and a great portion of the grade hinges on it. The project during my semester was to develop a webstite for advising scheduling using php and html, which we were expected to learn on our own. Very stressful semester, barely got a B. 331 is supposed to be easier imo.

Lupoli clearly is interested in and understands the course material, but sometimes has trouble conveying it to students. His lectures were pretty entertaining, but projects were a nightmare- the descriptions would change while we were supposed to be working on them, because students had to point out that requirements did not make sense.

He was Rude. The lectures are helpful but he doesn't even go over the slides and expects you to know them already. Doesn't respond to emails. His TA's were really helpful and nice. Some people find him funny but I thought he was really rude and he liked insulting people a lot. Gets really angry if you're even a second late to class.

His notes are worthless, he talks to you as if you are a window licking mouth breather; very condescending. 2 exams, 2 projects. If you really want to learn basics of coding, take it with some one more competent and professional.

Hard class. His notes were not easy to read... However I did have very minimal programming knowledge. The only students that knew seemed to know what was going on were the students who were experienced.

Dr. Oates has the potential to be a mainstream science communicator in this field. He's like a lighthouse in the sea of professor mediocrity that is UMBC. As a lecturer he is MOOC or elite university material. Would recommend this class but expect to work very hard especially if you don't have a background in probability theory. Worth it though.

Very good teacher. Heard a lot of complaints from the students taking Bergernon in the other section but none of the problems were in his class. He explained all the projects very clearly and was always helpful. He explained all the information needed very clearly too and we even moved faster than the other classes by a lot. A+

I'm really glad I picked him for my Master's Thesis. He is incredibly easy to get along with, patient, and helpful. Robotics is probably the coolest area in CS, and I couldn't imagine picking a better professor for the task.

John Park is the best professor in the CMSC program. His 313 class is much harder than other sections (we had 7 projects to another section's 2) but you learn so much more. I am taking 411 this semester and it is all pretty much review for the first half of the class thanks to Park. His tests and projects are tough, don't skip class!

Park is one of the best professors I have ever met in UMBC. Although it's super difficult to not fall asleep during his lectures, he's extremely helpful during office hours. DON'T expect to get any of your grades back. I have received my final grade for the class, but I still haven't heard a word about my project gr
Super smart guy, but unavailable for office hours most of the time. Projects are impossibly hard. Grades extremely slow so you won't know if you have a A or if you fail. Read the book for exams.

RIght guy for OS class. Park or his graders grade slowly, so you'll never know how you're doing in class. Park won't fail you as long as you try. He's a really smart dude and believes in us a little too much so last project could be rough if he doesn't dumb it down enough. Helps a lot outside of class with extra lectures.

Excellent instructor, lectures were very clear and concise. Very helpful if you go to him. Unfortunately, little to no use of the textbook, and takes some time to get grades back on regular assignments/projects.

I gave up lecture after 3 weeks and just attended them every so often, and when in class, surfed the web, and still got an A (no prior knowledge of C++ even). Bad to go to for questions but the book/online slides/labs got me through it easily. His exams are hard if you don't study (me) but I don't feel that you need to attend class ever to do well.
Impossible exams take class with someone else

Awful. He doesnt make the projects, he doesnt know the projects and he doesnt care about the students. All questions or issues are directed to the TA, and the TA has limited abilities to do anything for you. He is part time and it shows. Take it with Wortman or somebody else.

Not a good teacher. I expect a little seriousness when I am trying to learn, and I just gave up going to lectures because I couldn't take his jokes, and ended up getting a C. If you have a choice, anyone else is better. I looked at Prof. Chang's slides and those alone were SO much more informative compared to Raouf or his slides.

Raof trys to screw you at every turn. Take the class with Prof Cheng, he rewrote the entire cirriculum this semester. Raof trys to make impossible exams and gives no guidance for the projects; you are completly on your own. Luckily for me, a great TA Dom Miner, rewrote and made the exams relatively easy and gave direction and help with the projects

I took 202 with Raouf because of all the reviews, and I was misled. If you want a good grade, then sit in the front row and laugh at his bad jokes. I wrote him 4 emails over the summer about my 79% in the course; he didn't respond to one, I had to take it over with Wortman. She is a much nicer professor and she cares about all her students.

He's a good TEACHER, but he really lacks as a PROFESSOR. Rarely did he know anything about the projects, or what was going on in the course outside of lecture. His ridiculous midterm also weeds out the idiots that think they can major in comp sci cause they burned a CD once, but if you stick it out till the end, it's worth it.

Ridiculously difficult tests, but at least he will work with you and try and help. However, he knows very little about the projects and homework, as he had little to do with writing them :(. however, overall, still a very good teacher.

She doesn't seem particularly interested in the material of the class, but that wasn't a problem. The exams, projects, and homework were all a reasonable level of difficulty. The class was challenging but at that same time very manageable. TAs were not particularly useful so labs and projects were very hard, but that isn't the instructors fault.
She wasnt as bad as some comments are suggesting. Just a hard grader!!!

Many reviews on here I feel are biased since this is an intro to Computer Engineering course. Most freshman want grades handed to them. She makes you work and earn your grade. The class has been the same ( both exams and projects) since she started teaching it. Learn the material, don't just memorize it! She wants you to think outside the box.

Makes an easy class conceptually impossible to comprehend. Never keeps study material online, so if you want to even remotely prepare for exams you need to save everything she posts of everything, EVEN LABS Homework doesn't prepare you for exams. So you do a week of binary to see and get a hamming code question on the exam and just fail. AVOID.

Absolute worst professor I've ever had at UMBC. Gives a RAT (Readiness Assurance Test) every other Friday. Which is graded off of effort so you'll never really know if you get the concepts until the exams which are inconsistent, unclear and test esoteric concepts you'd never experience. AVOID

Confusing teacher. Lectures are generally read verbatim from a set of slides. The primary issue is that her exams are poorly written and vague and projects are extremely difficult. She often tells us how engineers will never use some of the difficult, abstract concepts she teaches in class and then proceeds to lecture and test us on them. AVOID.

Her lecture slides, and especially exams, are riddled with vague, confusing wording and grammar that always leads to confusion. This gets annoying because the TAs often don't understand what she meant on the tests either. Then she leaves the TAs alone in class to review exams, naturally... I don't get the feeling she cares much about this course.

She was really nice, but she can be very unclear. English isn't her first language, so her quiz/test questions can be vague. She often further confuses the question while explaining. Advice: If confused, ask. If you understand, then DON'T LISTEN to her explanation. Even if she says "You'll never use this info," she will still test you on it.

Assignments are extremely easy because he practically gives you the answers. The later assignments get a little harder, but they are all doable. His lectures are extremely boring though and all of the notes are on the website. I didn't do as well on the tests because of not getting the material in class. I hear he curves generously though.

He's nice, but his teaching skills leave something to be desired. Homeworks require some mulling around on the website or textbook to figure out because lectures aren't that helpful. Luckily the "projects" typically involve 20 lines of code max, and practice exams are almost identical to actual exams. Plus he gives 1/3 of the class an A.
There's a reason why his sections fill up immediately

An easy professor, if that's what you want. I wished I'd learned more in his class. He tells you exactly what he expects, and exactly how to do the homework (down to showing you where to type) which makes it less than difficult to do the work.

Great guy, makes not-funny jokes that actually make you laugh. Class is boring as hell, he knows a lot and is an expert but he's bad at teaching, really. Projects can be way complicated compared to other sections but he's reasonable when grading and also giving online quizes and exams.

If you (like me) don't care about programming (Java) and dont want to be one, he's the easiest professor. No problem getting a B or A. If you do want to be a programmer and learn more advanced Java, I'd suggest to take a better professor. Although he knows a lot and has vast experience, he is bad on teaching, very bad.

He is a horrible teacher. He doesn't care about being there. He gives take home quizzes, which is probably the only reason why I passed. He doesn't explain anything and just reads off of the books PowerPoints, he is so lazy and he doesn't give timely feedback--still waiting on grades from before the midterm and classes are over.

Professor Vick is a pretty cool teacher in general, his exams are fairly easy (simple questions from slides/book), and he is very lenient with deadlines. However, in terms of teaching, he's not very clear and his writing on the board is almost incomprehensible. He requires peer programming for projects, my suggestion don't pick a crappy partner.

I'm not sure if I should suggest Vick or tell you to run away. I ended up getting an A in his class but I can't say it was easy. He's not very clear on assignments and seems to have a strange grading system. We did peer programming which was both a blessing and a curse. Helpful tip: Pick a good partner and you'll be fine. Exams are easy as all hell

No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No No. Vick is very nice and funny, but in my top 3 of worst professors ever. Doesn't explain things well, makes everything overly cryptic. 3 quizes, a take home mdtrm, 3 prjts, final exam. Sounds okay, but is waayy to hard, considering his teaching ability. Get in groups.

The nicest, most lenient prof you'll meet. The worst teacher you can take. 331 is not supposed to be difficult but Vick turns it into intro to compiler theory. Cannot explain anything clearly, even after numerous tries. Seems to enjoy making subject overly cryptic. Likes to call on ppl when it's clear they have no clue. 3/4 of the class was lost.
WAYYYY too hard. expects you to know every single thing he teaches. STAY AWAY!

This professor is a lot better than everyone thinks. People who can't be expected to take "take home" exams seriously should not register in his course. Once you try, you will realize how easy his classes are. True, he could be a bit more explainitory, but if you're not understanding his lectures, chances are others aren't either. Curves favorably!
He's probably a follower of Socrates because all he'd do is ask the class questions.

Probably my least favorite professor thus far. He just reads off of 10 year old powerpoint slides and doesn't speak loudly or encourage you to listen. There are two exams worth 80% of your grade (the final is 50%) and about 5 homeworks to cover the rest. Going to his lectures is utterly useless, so you will wind up reading the textbook to learn.

I don't know why people complain about this man. I went to 2 classes the entire semester and those were the tests. I got an A. Yes he's hard to understand and yes he's boring. Worst instructor I've had in my life and I'm not exaggerating. Lectures are worthless and he's hard to understand. He was not very good at explaining things BUT his exams were all open book and open notes. If you can learn from the text then take his class, learn from the text and skip class. horrible teacher, takes like a month to grade exams.. all 2 of them. talks very slowly and goes over 1 thing for the entire class. didn't even complete all of the material described in the syllabus but yet its still on the final which is 50% with 5 questions which is ridiculous. NOT RECOMMENDED.

what a joke! AVOID him if yo want to learn. take him if you want an easy A. 50% of your grade final exam with about 5 questions. 4 easy questions from HWs and one that you might have no idea. I got an A but I'm not sure what I learned from it...

Not bad. Mid/final are 4 questions each, so you better know the proofs (PUMPING LEMMA haah). 2 or 3 hw. That's it for grading. Wow! You will feel very lost in the first 1/2 of the semester because all he does is read off the slides. Once he starts posting homework and gives exams you will find his course is extremely easy. Best teacher for 203. Very entertaining, which is important for such a dense subject. Exams from '93 are available on his website. Only 4 short homework assignments (compared to weekly homework in other sections) and drops your lowest hw, exam, inclass.
Clearly explains what you need to know and has all old exams available to students.
Not necesarily the easiest class ive ever taken, but he did try to work with us to explain everything. Very helpful if you needed it.
He posts old exams and they are the same every semester. He just changes the values in the problems.
Very understanding professor. The projects are really the only hard part of the class, and he normally gives a lot of help on them. He is also very lenient on exams
Best 202 teacher. He is very approachable and answers any questions you have during office hours.
This course is nothing like 201. You have to work from the start of the class to the end. Great teacher. His office hours are the best place to get help! Taking his CMSC 341 course
Easy lecture to sit through. Exams are very different when compared to 201. Pay attention to examples done in class, they help! He is very approachable and is always willing to answer questions.
Very funny and down to earth guy that wants to help. Extremely helpful in his office hours.
Every single assignment has been full of errors. He is sloppy and slow to respond to emails. When he does, the answers are useless. AVOID AT ALL COSTS.
Make sure you attend class. Hardest part of the class is using CVS. Go to his office if you have any questions because he is very personable and wants to make sure you understand the material.
He has assignments full of errors and gets incredibly defensive when these errors are mentioned. Also the answer keys he gives the TAs are wrong.
The lecture slides are online and the exams are based off of the study guides. Easy A. Attend class to participate in group work.

Mrs. Block is one of my favorite professors. She is very helpful through email and in just talking to her. The TAs were also very helpful and the homeworks weren't very hard. Exams are made up of questions from the study guide so just do that before the exam. Grades very generously.
She's prompt with responding to emails, lectures clearly, and is overall very reasonable with workload. She also brings candy to class!

The best teacher at UMBC. I had her for 201 back in the Spring of 2008 and even to this day passing in the hall she will address me by name and inquire after my studies. Very good teacher. Cares for the students.

Extremely clear professor. I went into 104 having had no prior programming experience and am now in 313 and 331 and having no trouble. This is thanks to her! She made the class so fun and enjoyable but also made sure that everyone was learning what they needed to in order to be successful in 201... and beyond!

The Best Professor at UMBC. If you graduate without taking her easy CMSC 104 class, you are really missing out. She is HOT!! Not just the guys but even the girls think so! She is sweet and goes out of her way to help her students. You get chocolate if you go visit her in her office. She will take time out for you. Take her! She is Fantabulous!!

Ms.Block is extremely helpful if she sees that you are trying to your full potential. Brings in candies on holidays & exam days!! Easy to understand and easy to approach. He does not answer questions, would not recommend his class

DO NOT TAKE HIM, He is the reason why so many people fell his class and switch to IS majors. would not recommend. He is not helpful and does not answer your questions directly. Overall not a helpful teacher.

try to take someone else! he's very confused and spent atleast 3 classes learning how to do something himself so he could teach, claiming the dept. is making him do it and he doesnt want/know how to do it. Fair grader. Only 10 days allowed for each project, which was tight.

Great Professor. Very clear. Has an assignment due every week, but with a forgiving late policy. Only complaint is that it sometimes took a while to get grades back. Would highly recommend taking him.
Chang is my favorite professor so far. He is extremely smart and is a true nerd. He is very approachable and has an interest in what he is teaching.

It's important to realize how bad this CMSC/CMPE professor really is. His exams and his projects are ridiculously hard. He gives out difficult GRADED homework assignments during finals week. I have had 2 classes with him, and i would NOT recommend anyone take him for any class. he has typos on projects. wrong data on Exam which he didnt show up for and TA had to spend 15 min trying to get hold of him. his exam review consist of "read entire book". boring lectures and he cant teach, all he does is read from ppt provide by book author.

Awesome professor. She is the friendliest woman on campus and will really help you out when you need it. Knows her material and is a great ease into the computer science program at the school. Highly recommended!

Like was said below-- the lectures are boring but she is nice and gives a fair class. the mid/final is made up from a list of Qs that SHE GIVES YOU before! she posts lecture slides online which she reads from anyways. Don't listen to the haters, if every teacher was like him UMBC would graduate more than 34%. Grades on an all-or-nothing basis. No partial credit. Ex: on the exams, you're given a 10pt tree of some sort and you have to insert / remove 5 nodes. Horrible teacher, Half of his class weren't there, I later found out it's because they were retaking the class in fault because of his bad grading, meaning statistically, 1/4 of his students have to go to another school to take this class. Mr. Frey is a really good instructor with a lot of experience in the actual comp sci world ... designed lottery system for some state. Very good. Loves to teach. Post lectures online. Tests are straight forward and fair. 5 projects, 3 tests.

Do not take this class. The class is about networking, the different layers and standards. I am currently working as a networking engineer and struggled due to his ridiculous policies. Tests are insane, have nothing to do with anything we talked about. Avoid his class altogether

He curves at the end of the semester

Projects? Hard. Homework? Lots. Exams? Very Hard. Lecture style? Superb! Very knowledgeable; really wants to see students succeed. Be prepared to work very hard and learn lots of really useful stuff; recruiters were very interested in this class and the projects.
Easy class, easy material, teacher does his job, and does it fairly well. He's got some old school ideas, and is deffinitely a conservative. Gotta love it.

bad teacher, would not recommend, terrible handwriting, can't hear a word, never explains what he writes, and does not have online notes and doesn't give out his notes to copy, be prepared for the handwriting race of you life
this guy is old..but he likes teaching...hot girls beware he will be staring down your tops
Give this guy some credit, This is the easiest class in the world.

NEEDS TO RETIRE! Dr. Katz is mildly deaf, which wastes a lot of teaching time because he does not hear the answers being called out. This class does well slowly introducing foreign material to those new to compsci, but DOES NOT HELP YOU FOR CMSC 201! DON'T TAKE KATZ IF YOU PLAN TO TAKE CMSC 201!!

was a rocket scientist and if you ask a question, he tells you "It's not rocket science!" and expects you to know it.supposed to be an intro for 201 but he expects you to already know the material (which he just reads slides that you can access on the internet). hw is easy but midterm is too hard.
whoa... be prepared to write furiously and understand nothing. Buy the book, and read that. end of story

He's got a hearing aide, so help him out a little, and SPEAK UP! He can hear fine. The key to passing his class is his PAST EXAMS! Find them! Sell your soul for them! Interesting to talk to. Extremely intelligent. How often do you get a former rocket scientist as a professor?

katz knows his computer material although he cant present it very well. his age can be a problem for students since he doesnt hear very well. his exams are straight from the book and are relatively easy. i got an A and barely showed up to class.
I won't recommend anyone to take course with him, he's the worst professor you could find and you won't learn anything from him and they way he grade is awful.

He was the course coordinator for the class I took with a different instructor. Managed to screw up something on every project and changedclarified 3-4 times per project. Comes across as arrogant and grading can sometimes be suspect.

He is an amazing teacher

Best professor I've had at UMBC bar none. Dr. Oates is AWESOME. He works very hard to engage his students and to make the material (which is pretty hard) easy to understand. Excellent teacher. Very clear in teaching and slows down when he needs to. Grades fairly leniently and definitely wants his students to pass. Data Structures is tough. Dr. Oates is clear, easygoing and a lenient grader.

Park is the best CS professor I have had at UMBC. Professor Park is amazing. His lectures are helpful and easy to follow. Projects are extremely difficult but you're given ample time. He will help if you go to him to ask questions. Don't expect to get any grades back but grading will be fair.

Don't expect to get grades back. Don't expect him to return e-mails. Expect to get the grade you earned. His lecture notes only make sense IF YOU GO TO LECTURE!! Very helpful; he stayed after class multiple times to help me with things I was confused on. Projects are well written. If you want to learn, TAKE THIS GUY!

I took this course the first semester they returned back to C++, originally taken it in Java and had many problems with that professor. John is an excellent professor he will VERY often answer a question with "it depends", with very good reason because he is extremely smart and knows a lot about his field. He is a teacher that wants to be fair to those that put in the effort to do well in the class. I recommend him.

a lot of people are saying that he is a great teacher and thats why i took the class with him....hes only helpful to the people who he knows by name, the people who sit in the front... if you dont sit in the front and participate in class... hes not exactly the nicest guy... he repeats himself entire way too much... take it with Wortman

Most unorganized unclear professor

I you want to pass 310 do not take this class with this professor, though she is very helpful and approachable the class is extremely demanding. She gives biweekly quizzes and they are exams.

Nice old guy, really smart. Unfortunately, he can't teach. At all. He is very helpful on his projects. If you go to him for help don't be surprised if he basically finished it for you. His lectures are well organized and he has code samples in a ton of programming languages. Very nice guy.

Assignments were easy overall. However, at the end of the semester, he changed his grade breakdown from what the syllabus originally said. His grading was really inconsistent and many students received grades lower than they actually earned. I would avoid this professor for this class.
Dr. Squire's Hardware Course is pretty simple and straight forward. He does everything he can to help you pass the course.

Notes/lectures on the website. HW and projects get progressively harder. HW eventually strays away from the notes, so it gets frustrating to find answers. Can be rude on random days. Exams are multiple choice. Just study off the past exams he gives. Curve is dependent on how smart the top 1/3 are as 1/3 gets A. No guidance on Proj after part 1.

I highly recommend Professor Squire for anything you can take with him. He goes over exactly what he expects you to know for every assignment and is extremely helpful in office hours. He even tells you straight up that the tests are made to be easy.

take him !!!! U shud wait untill he teaches coz its the easiest cmsc class u evr take... Imagine a class easier than CMSC 201. Thats what it like.. HE gives out his questions before both exams so all u gotta do is memorize them.

Ah fun times with Vick. So I had to repeat this God aweful class, took him the first time only person available the second. Fun Times. :P. I oounted a total of 6 graded materials. Midterm and Final are takehome, prepare to be amazed at how hard something you have all week to do is

Avoid this teacher at all costs. He is almost always late to class. He "scolded" us for leaving early once because he was over 20 minutes late. HE CAN'T TEACH.HE DOES EVEN DO EYE CONTACT. NOBODY LISTENS IN HIS CLASS. HE TALKS SO SLOW...SPENDS 40MINS ON ONE SLIDE.

If Rain Man were a teacher, his name would be Yaakov Yesha. I had maintained a 4.0 GPA through 6 semesters prior to my ill fated experience with "Rain Man". His communication skills are non-existent. He's a cool guy. I think that he's hot, but I like the shape of penguins and ellipses.

Has an evil twin that he calls the ?GRADER? (cough cough). If your answers aren't a verbatim copy of his - you'll lose massive pts - even if right. Good prof,knows wht hes talkin abt and teaching,class is a bit mundane and sometimes hard to stay awake so factor that in,grade based on 3 in classes,4hws,2tests,participation,and final exam.but 2 tests and final worth 300 out of 400 points.100% on other assignments completed.Tests since '93 available online,easy to get points,good curve
Very easy teacher. Helps out whenever you need it. Tests are somewhat difficult, but are very passable, if you pay attention.
Not a great professor by any means, but he is the best to take for 203.

Excellent professor. The class is a lot different from 201 - you really have to work to understand the material. He's an excellent lecturer - I learned a TON in his class. Great teacher.

Pretty funny and engaging. Also very personable. Sometimes explains concepts in a weird way. Enforces object oriented programming heavily in this course. He's definitely the best Computer Science professor I've had. The projects can be really hard if you're new to computer science, but truly make you think hard about design choices. Attendance isn't "mandatory", but if you want to do well, attend lectures. Besides, they are often fun to listen to. Feel free to go to his office hours, he's friendly.

He's very friendly and approachable, and likes to chat with students before class. He occasionally can become confusing when he starts teaching more to the sector who programs frequently in their free time. I liked him enough to take 341H with him, though, so overall he's pretty good.
Having had her for 104 and 201, I will say that if you don't get to have a class with her you are missing out. Just an all around great prof.

One of the best teachers at UMBC. Quite funny and brings candy to class once in a while. She's young and always smiling so you can associate with her easily. If you haven't taken programming before, she should be your pick! Also for CMSC 201!
Clear lectures, posts the slides. Available for questions via email anytime. What more could you want?
Amazing, one of the best teachers I've had my freshman year
She is one the most helpful and passionate teachers I've ever had. She not only is willing to help you succeed in her class, she will also help you outside of class with advising type issues.
Great teacher, very clear and helpful. tests are not that hard, really easy if you study. computer programs are time consuming. great class to see if you want to major in computer science

One of the best professors i've had at UMBC. Def worth taking a class with her! Midterm & final is fairly easy if you complete the study questions she gives out a week prior to the exam. Very helpful, funny, friendly & makes the course much more interesting than it really is. Brings in candy on exam days; this semester, she even brought ice cream:)

Ms. Block is great. i have nothing but respect for her. I have her as both my teacher and advisor for the last year and she's extremely helpful. She's a very happy person (smiles all the time). she will always help you with your code and everything and clear on what each project is suppose to do. you should def. take her. my fav. teacher ever.
Awesome teacher, very helpful, and very clear in lecture.

The best teacher Ive had. Discussion is mandatory, but helpful if you dont have much programming experience. I also had her for 104 and she is a very good teacher and makes an effort to learn everyones name. Shes even starting to sway me in CMSC minoring.

If ur used to programming, A is attainable with some effort. The 5 hmwrk assignments (writing large programs) are the time consuming part of the course. Lectures sometimes entertaining, usually boring. If do labs & homework, studying for exams should be simple. Just review lecture notes posted online. Nice, accommodating, flexible, cares abt stdnts

202 is a hard class, and he doesn't do much to ease you into coding in C++, but he explains the important stuff pretty clearly. The projects are tough, but he answers questions in class if you have any. Exams are pretty typical, but it's hard to study for them. He's great about returning emails and is generally very helpful.

Best CS professor I've had to date. For programming assignments, his write ups were incredibly well written. Though sometimes difficult, projects and homeworks are super valuable. Oh, and he's hilarious. If you want an easy A, avoid him. (Else) If you want to struggle, and learn a ton along the way, Chang's the real deal.

CMSC 313 with Dr. Chang has been my favorite course at UMBC so far. I may be alone in this, but I LOVE assembly language programming. Dr. Chang is a great professor and is extremely knowledgeable. The course is quite easy if you start the projects early in the week.

Great professor; made the lectures fun and understandable. Gave a 3 for easiness only because he had a program due every week; hard programs. Not a good class to take if you're taking a full-time schedule of courses and working at the same time. Hard to keep up if you miss classes, so even though attendance isn't mandatory, going is a good idea.

I really enjoyed this class. The programs we had to write were interesting and a nice challenge. He allows you to finish classwork outside of class if you have to. If you actually pay attention in the beginning of class instead of catching up on work, you'll probably do fine.
Hands down the best teacher I've had at UMBC. Always in a good mood, and actually cares about his students.

Chang is by far the best professor I've ever had. He's incredibly intelligent but also knows how to dumb things down for the rest of us. Very straightforward in what he expects, and tests and quizzes look exactly like what goes on in class and on the homework. If you can take 203 with him, do it. He's far better than anyone else who teaches it

This is a difficult class just because of the introduction of new mathematical concepts but I think that Dr. Chang does a really good job of explaining them. Lectures were very helpful. He's a pretty funny guy too, in a nerdy way.

He is an extremely nice guy. A very fair grader. His quizes are more like brain teasers than typical plug and chug questions of other teachers, but he gives plenty of partial credit. Basically, if you put in a reasonable amount of effort you should not fail his class.

Learned a lot from his lectures, even if he rambles on tangents. Brilliant man. Buck stops there though. Often condescending when answering Q's. Worthless with project help: his canned reply is to read the instructions. As 5/31/08 review said though, his instructions/rubrics are a mess of holes and contradictions. If you take him, you'll see. lol.

Very good at explaining things. Always willing to go over things again if your lost. Answers any question you might have. Easy to talk to about what bothers you about the class (we spent one entire class talking about how hard the midterm was).Teaches the material very well. I learned a lot with him. Exams/projects are hard but grading is lenient.
the most interesting class
nice person

Great professor. Extremely helpful and approachable. Her demo of binary search is great, so is her demo with using floating point numbers for equality comparison. Definitely helped increase my interest and understanding of computer science. A good part of CMSC 201 homework and project grades involve following standards, so be sure to follow them.

Easy for experienced programmers up until the midterm, then it gets more interesting. Labs are great and very helpful. Ms. Evans is very skilled at python, she zips through the examples. Everything from slides. Very sweet professor, slightly boring lecture, but good at explaining concepts.

Did a very good job at making this a class that does not make neither new programmers nor experienced programmers feel excluded. Understand the practice exam and you'll do fine on midterm/final. Programs due once a week. Labs very helpful with homework

201 can be a pretty challenging class. Mrs. Evans does her best to explain things but somethings can only be learned by doing them. Class attendance is not mandatory, but I would certainly say that class attendance and good grades have a very strong relationship in 201. Never forget printGreeting() and always use constants!

Great teacher. The lectures were straightforward and on powerpoint type things for later usage. You could pretty much not go to class, though, like the majority did. Labs are easy. Final project is a bit complicated compared to the rest of the course, but the assignments and other projects were very easy. Highly recommended.

Excellent instructor. Material present in a way that is easy to understand, and it's easy to remain engaged. Very accessible to speak with and helpful if you have a problem. Would recommend any class that she teaches.

This class is pretty darn easy and not very time-consuming, provided you pay attention in class (especially when she's talking about the projects)/read the lecture notes. Evans is a good lecturer and she's good with questions.
One of the best teachers here, no doubt. She fired back up my passion for computer science and was perfectly helpful in every way.

One of the best UMBC professors at UMBC. Assembly looked hard and scarey and he made me understand it. Can be hard, but it's because the material is hard. Study hard and you'll do well. I recommend this teacher.

Explains things very clearly in lecture. You will learn a lot if you apply yourself dilligently, but your grade will not show this -> his tests are very tricky and usually pushed me to the time limit. Busted my butt in the class but only wound up with a B. Projects are pretty difficult and if you go to office hours he kind of makes you feel dumb

Frey has some magical ability to explain anything to anyone in a way they can understand. Tests are difficult, though not unreasonable. If you study hard, then you will learn a lot from him and probably get a good grade.
Knows his stuff and explains it well. Grades fairly.
Very good teacher, one of the best at UMBC. Was very helpful, the tests are alittle hard but other than that I loved the class.

Very good at explaining material. Usually helpful with projects if you go see him. DO NOT TRUST THE TA's. They notoriously gave incorrect information to many students. This course is hard just because his tests are a bit difficult. Also the TA's dont take the time to grade projects with integrity. Work hard and go to office hours. U'll b grea

Frey made assembly really interesting and accessible. He's hilarious and always really clear on what you need to be learning. The projects, though not unique to this school, are fascinating, challenging, and rewarding. Frey also really prepared us well in this course for the operating systems course!

Mr. Frey is definitely one of the best teachers I have ever had. He has a good sense of humor and he is is friendly and approachable, yet he commands respect. He obviously knows his material and he explains it very clearly. I recommend him to all my CMSC/CMPE friends.

Very friendly and approachable. This semester's course was a pilot so he wasn't accurate on all the information (esp. hardware architecture), but was more than willing to be corrected. Has a tendency to mix up terms when he's lecturing but is a good teacher nonetheless.

I dont know what those two lames below me are talking about but Frey is one of the best teachers ive had so far..taking this class with him is a no brainer...he knows almost everything, can help with projects cuz he makes them, and hes approachable...the only reason you dont take it with him is if the class is full..def. recommended for Majors

There are about 8-10 pop quizzes per semester. My best advice is to read the chapters ahead of class time. Follow the guidelines in the syllabus for submitting HW (he is picky about copy & paste vs. attachments). Attend class so that you do not miss details on Exams. Exams are very difficult. The final grading criteria is slightly curved.

Do NOT recommend! It is a fast pace course with a lot of material to cover. You only learn if you read the book before class, he gives pop quizzes. Chapters & slides are about 100pgs. Lost points on hw because of format (bullets not sentences) but was unaware as they were graded after all were completed & quizzes had very tricky questions.

Easy class, hard exams. He's a nice guy though. Make sure you participate every day to get your full participation points. Easy B, but you'll have to decipher the [sometimes] confusing wording of his exams to get an A.
This is a great teacher... Do NOT listen to DUMB IS ppl. well, IS guys are complaining cuz this guy is an engineer and he teaches as an engineer. But for CMPE or CMSC, this guy is great.

great teacher. brings a lot of real world material to the class. very knowledgible person in IS,CMSC arena. He speaks too fast so sometimes its hard to understand what he says. His grading is very fair and questions are straight from his slides. DO ANSWER CHECKPOINT QUESTIONS !!!! AND POP QUIZES coz that can decide whather u get a C or A

This is one of the easiest CMPE courses you will ever take. It's a class about cell phones, so it's interesting. He's quite possibly the funniest CMPE professor, and he's normally a IFSM professor, so the exams are really easy. He pulls the exact same questions from slides and puts them on exams. Memorization is a key.

One of my favorite lecturers at UMBC. He'll explain something as many times as necessary until you understand, and he's always ready to help you after class or during office hours. Tests are incredibly difficult. You can't do well without closely reading the book and attending class. Luckily he'll curve generously if you show effort or interest.

Class required work, project was difficult and there were issues with the project architecture as put together by the TA. But professor was understanding and helpful. Tests closely followed homework, if you do it and review it, you should expect a good grade. Is a very animated teacher, very interested in subject. Felt I learned a lot.

Others say he is a great professor -- I have to disagree. Yes, he is engaging as a lecturer, but he is a very unfair prof. Tests are multiple choice which doesn't make sense for this subject. Questions on tests had multiple right answers, which was not revealed until later. I'd avoid taking him, even though he's a good lecturer.

Great Professor! You will learn tons of interesting things. He will make your programming HWs be like projects and your projects will take you days, but you will say thank you in the end. I think all classes should be taught like this. If you have a little extra time during your semester take it with Kalpakis.

Overrated in both difficulty and approachability. Expects no more from you than many other profs. If you're a CMPE or MATH major, you won't flinch over workload. Also seems a bit bipolar: sometimes very friendly + engaging, but other times very cold + impatient. Never replies to emails. lol. Lectures are definitely top notch though: A+++ there.
Just read the book. You'll be straight.

Katz just reads the power point slides and that's it! i changed my major becasue of him! but the classs is easy overall. he gives you a master list for each exams! the final is very easy!! ( but don't really count on him to help you a lot! READ THE BOOK!!!!!)
Easy class. Bad attitude. Did he even read the term papers? Ask him a question and he doesn't comprehend why you don't already know the answer. Doesn't seem to want to be teaching.

This class is basically a web development course. You learn HTML, CSS, PHP, SQL, Javascript and Bash. Every class is a graded lab based on the reading, with an online quiz. You will be in a group for labs and 2 group projects. It can be a lot of work to keep up with, but you learn a lot and it's good for your resume. Grading is lenient in the end.

Best CS professor at UMBC. Not easy, but fair. You will know your stuff after a class with Lupoli, that is if you put in the effort. Better yet, the stuff you will know actually matters and will get you hired because of it. Tests are hard, study for them.

I thoroughly enjoyed Mr. Lupoli's humor in class and I think he is a great lecture-er. Class was tough but I sure learned a lot. His exams are fair to what he asks of you to study. His final was really hard but I got a 99, and he gives a lot of partial credit as long as you explained the process. I love a teacher that you can sass back!

My favorite thing about Mr. Lupoli is that he actually cared about our success; he would be hard on us to make us better. When I submitted a project that I know I didn't do well on, it felt like I was really letting him down, and it made me want to do better. Do be aware that he does poke fun sometimes, and just don't take it personally.

Amazing lectures, he provides lots of notes, and is genuinely interested in our well being. he takes time to help us and when there's a problem. it was easy to resolve grading issues. better read the book; his lectures cleared up everything that was unclear, and he did this intentionally. i learned a lot

Lupoli is overall an awesome person; listen in his lectures, and MAKE SURE to ask him questions. He has an interesting sense of humor (dry and slapstick), so beware if you are a sensitive soul, because he likes to poke fun harmlessly.

Good professor overall, manages to keep lectures entertaining with a blunt humor style(which some might take offense to but I found it funny). I already had plenty of experience with Python so I mostly showed up for the tidbits/tricks that might appear on the tests(2 worth 50% of your grade programming class!) and he covered those well.

May have had a sufficient understanding of java and Data Structures, but failed to demonstrate so. Loopy Lecturer: Notes that he wrote himself give you the impression that he rarely programs professionally. Data structures is too important a class. Don't take it with him. That said: Nice guy, Very approachable, funny.

Great teacher, explains concepts with real life examples and in both technical/mathematical and layman terms. Assignments help better your understanding of concepts and expose you to analyses and the scientific idea synthesis process.
Lectures were amazing and crystal clear
Great professor who makes complex topics sound simple.
He is funny at time and serious at times but makes sure everyone gets the subject matter.
One of the best professor at UMBC. His classes are interesting. Pay attention and you sail through Easy exams

Great prof, great lectures, very engaging. Grading and assignments clearly explained. He is current on the material. Class was a good mix of theory and practical exercises. Moderately difficult but he was a lenient grader - most students made As or Bs on the exams. Missed a couple lectures, announced beforehand.

Outstanding lecturer & computer scientist. I would not call the class easy, but the professor makes it more than worth your effort in the amount of useful knowledge and expertise gained in this core CS topic. Recommended.. A++++ would take again. :)

Third course I've taken with Dr. Oates. He's clear, fair, and super available for helping students. He cares about what you think and about your success. Hint: take notes on paper without lines, he likes to draw graphs and it will make your notes much neater if there are no lines.
Excellent professor, very engaged and loves questions and making sure everyone understands.
Hes a very good/smart professor but more importantly a great guy..if hes teaching this course (or any for that matter) TAKE IT

Excellent teacher. Very knowledgeable and laid back about the material. Tries, and usually succeeds, in engaging the class. Cuts the material into manageable sizes and is understanding about difficulties and issues with homework and projects.

Cares about his students. Exams may be hard at first, but he'll adjust according to the class's needs (first exam average 68%, second exam average 106%). More than willing to allow extra time if you give enough advance notice. Lots of extra credit chances. Lenient grader on projects, available for help if you need it. Highly recommended.
Very knowledgeable and helpful.

Definitely take Oates if you get a chance to! Very student friendly and makes the material very easy to understand. No surprises on exams, he does a review the class before that will help you tremendously. Projects are mostly graded on execution correctness, so make sure they work!

Park is a kind and helpful professor; you will learn a lot. That said, his projects are quite difficult. Start right away! I worked hard and still got a C in the course. I would recommend him, while also saying consider another professor if you really need to get a good grade.

Park is very interested and knowledgeable in the material he covers. He talks a little quietly, but if you pay attention, you will learn a lot, and he is great at explaining concepts in ways that make intuitive sense. Very fair homeworks and exams; stays true to the review sheet. Great lecture slides, fair grader

Excellent professor. Harvard and Stanford graduate, worked in every industry you can think of. You probably won't get anything graded back, but you'll get the grade that you earned. He knows his stuff.

I'm still waiting on my project 2 grade, and by that I mean don't expect your grades back ever. The grades in the class are decided purely by tests and also magic. But other than the grading he is an amazing professor who cares about his students. He knows a lot about the industry and is always open to answer questions.
One of the best professors at UMBC
Probably one of the best professors at UMBC. He has the ability to explain things really well and also has absolute mastery of the subject. Also a great guy and really easy to talk to.

Professor Park is incredibly smart and seemingly always willing to help - even if you catch him outside of office hours. Projects and homework can be a bit tricky, so START EARLY and understand what you have to do before diving in. Grading takes awhile, but that's understandable. Lectures are clear and follow the textbook. Highly recommended.

First and foremost, Dr. Park is boring. But at the same time, he is one of the most interesting people you will ever meet. His grading is VERY generous. And if you put in some effort into his class and complete your assignments you'll get an A. He's an excellent professor, I highly recommend him. Just don't be surprised if you get sleepy.

Dr. Park is very knowledgeable, and he lectures well. His tests were a good measure of everything he taught. If you attended class (or even just took his lecture slides off blackboard), you should earn an easy A. Projects were a little challenging, but easily possible. Homeworks are standard for all sections of 201.

Sa'ad's class rocks. Always enjoyable and doesnt drag on like other classes. He knows the material very, very well, and takes the time to make sure that everyone(not just those he knows the names of like other claim) understands it completely. Would recommend, definitely knows what he is doing.

Professor Raouf is one of the best profs at UMBC. He not only cares about the lecture material but also cares about students as well. (If you make yourself known and participate in class.) Projects are created/assigned by Wortman but Raouf has his own tests. Prepare yourself for a very difficult midterm but the final has lots of extra credit.
The best professor I ever had
the professor is awesome! make you feel proud of your choice of major

Great teacher. Funny and knows the material very, very well. Tests are indeed ridiculously difficult - tries to be very tricky with the questions. Very strict about classroom discipline. One of my favorite teachers here. Communication is difficult - tends to be slow to answer emails, etc.
Great comp sci teacher.
very good teacher
Probably the best TEACHER I have had here. Makes you understand, goes at a very decent pace. Emphasizes what is important. Good humor too. I recommend taking him.
I had him last semister and I do like the way he make cyber topics intersting. You should take his class it is good one.

I really learn a lot in this class. If you study you will do well in his class and I know few students think he my be easy but let me tell you he is not. Excellent learning and if you want to understand anything in cyber he is the one.

He absolutely does NOT know his stuff. Let me put it this way--you're not being graded on your knowledge, so no amount of studying will help. You're being graded on how well you can guess what HE thinks the right answer is. About 20% of all his questions have incorrect/multiple answers. He will not go back and correct his own mistakes. Good luck

Great professor who knows how to make lecture interesting.He knows his stuff!!Very update and well organized.Clear about what he wants on the exams.If you want to get a good grade you HAVE TO study hard.Highly recommended!

She gets mixed up which mixes you up. Says she wants to foster an environment for learning, but will not allow you to take notes on devices of any kind and if further clarification is needed she debases the class by exclaiming "Come on guys. This is easy" and lets out a frustrated sigh. Overall if you can avoid her, you'll do yourself a favor.
This class is a lot of work. Learn assembly before taking it.

Professor Squire is an awesome guy and very knowledgeable. His classes are never the most rigorous but he's often teaching electives so they don't have to be. Exams are multiple choice and coding projects are very manageable. If you're swamped with classes and need to fit in a CS elective any Squire class will be a joy to take.

He is easy. You will pass, but he is EXTREMELY rude. If you are in the class to actually learn, forget it. He will tell you the answer and if you ask why, he will say don't worry about it. If you just want to pass with an A or B, take his class. If you actually want to learn, don't.
This class was a breath of fresh air for a summer course. Nice way to wind down the year.
TAKE IT WITH HIM. WORK A LIL BIT AND YOU WILL GET AN A

Squire is an excellent professor. His exams were fairly easy; just memorize the old exams that he gives you as a guide. Also, his homeworks and programs are not that difficult. If you do really well on his exams and attempt at the program, you'll be guaranteed a B.
Very good instructor, makes it very clear what the students need to know and does not burden them with unimportant busy work or unneeded information.

The class is extremely easy. You do not need to go to class, he passes last year's midterm and final exam back with answers the day before tests, and if you're a CMPE then you've seen the course content before in 310. And the project is cake. He practically gives you the code.

Prof. Vick is probably the best option for ANY IS major taking IS247. He assigns problems from the book but gives plenty of time to do them just don't wait. Start early, and you can code with a buddy (He favors Peer Programming highly). He's funny and jokes with you during lecture. Beware of his doctor's handwriting on the dry erase board.

I haven't received any grades yet but feel compelled to say AWESOME PROF! He falls way behind in lectures but always offers help. Very friendly. Grading might be somewhat harsh but gives plenty of time to do assignments. Has a sense of humor and classes are not stressful. He is in total favor of Peer-Programming (ie: with a buddy) on projects.
As said before, very lenient and fun to talk to, but is not great at actually teaching the material at hand. Get in groups.

Vick knows a lot about computer science, and you can learn a ton from him if you want to. His assigned readings are there for a reason, and lecture is a supplement to those. If you read the reading, and follow along in class, the class is great; if you rely on lecture alone, you will fail. He is more concerned with learning than grades.

Vick is the ultimate double-edged sword of professors. On one side he's funny, approachable, and interacts a lot with the class. On the other side though he's probably the least effective lecturer i've ever had. He's liberal with curves but even with them you will likely struggle to get B's. If you study his powerpoints outside class, you'll do ok.
I came to college and I pay to learn, taking this class you will not learn anything by the end, if you want to have a good experience and stay engaged do not take this class.

Decent instructor, speaks quietly has a pretty thick accent, but after a week or two it is very easy to understand him. Assigns readings, helpful if your lost but unnecessary to do well. Homeworks are easy, tests are mostly based on in class examples and homeworks. Tests are usually 4-6 questions, and worth most of your grade.
